  <h1 id="top">Descriptive Statistics &amp; Hypothesis Testing</h1>
  <p>Descriptive stats (mean/variance/z-score) appears every year. Formal inference (CI &amp; tests) hasn't been directly tested 2024–2026 — learn the fundamentals, but don't over-invest.</p>
</div>

<!-- ═══ THEORY 1: DESCRIPTIVE STATISTICS ═══ -->
<h2 id="descriptive">Theory — Descriptive Statistics</h2>
<p style="font-size:15px;color:var(--gd-text-1);margin-bottom:16px;line-height:1.6;">
  Summarizing data with numbers. The $\div n$ vs $\div(n-1)$ distinction for variance is the single most-tested subtlety in this section.
</p>

<div class="rules-grid">
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Central tendency</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$\bar&#123;x&#125; = \frac&#123;1&#125;&#123;n&#125;\sum_&#123;i=1&#125;^n x_i, \qquad \bar&#123;x&#125;_w = \frac&#123;\sum w_i x_i&#125;&#123;\sum w_i&#125;$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;"><strong>Median</strong> — middle value (sorted); robust to outliers. <strong>Mean</strong> — pulled by outliers. <strong>Mode</strong> — most frequent.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Variance — population (÷n) vs sample (÷n−1)</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$\sigma^2 = \frac&#123;1&#125;&#123;n&#125;\sum(x_i-\bar&#123;x&#125;)^2 \quad \text&#123;(population)&#125;$$</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$s^2 = \frac&#123;1&#125;&#123;n-1&#125;\sum(x_i-\bar&#123;x&#125;)^2 \quad \text&#123;(sample)&#125;$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">Bessel's correction: $\div(n-1)$ makes $s^2$ unbiased. $\text&#123;SD&#125; = \sqrt&#123;\text&#123;variance&#125;&#125;$.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">z-score normalization</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$z = \frac&#123;x - \bar&#123;x&#125;&#125;&#123;s&#125;$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">How many SDs a value sits from the mean. $z \approx 0$: typical. $|z| > 2$: unusual. min/max are distractors — use mean and SD only. (2024 Q27)</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Effect of linear transformations</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$x_i \to x_i + c: \quad \bar&#123;x&#125; \mathrel&#123;+&#125;= c, \quad \sigma^2 \text&#123; unchanged&#125;$$</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$x_i \to k x_i: \quad \bar&#123;x&#125; \to k\bar&#123;x&#125;, \quad \sigma^2 \to k^2\sigma^2, \quad s \to |k|s$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">Shifting leaves spread unchanged. Scaling multiplies variance by $k^2$, SD by $|k|$.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-insights">
  <div class="gd-insight gd-insight--warn">
    <span class="gd-insight__title">The $\div n$ vs $\div(n-1)$ trap — read the problem carefully</span>
    When the question says "population variance" or gives the entire dataset → $\div n$. When it says "sample variance" or "$s^2$" → $\div(n-1)$. Using the wrong divisor is the most common slip on descriptive-stats questions. (2026 Q62 is built around this identity.)
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ THEORY 2: HYPOTHESIS TESTING ═══ -->
<h2 id="testing">Theory — Hypothesis Testing Framework</h2>
<p style="font-size:15px;color:var(--gd-text-1);margin-bottom:16px;line-height:1.6;">
  A formal procedure for deciding between two competing claims about a population. The five-step framework below applies to every z-, t-, and $\chi^2$-test.
</p>

<div class="rules-grid">
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">1 · Hypotheses &amp; significance level</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$H_0: \mu = \mu_0 \;(\text&#123;null&#125;) \qquad H_1: \mu \ne \mu_0 \;(\text&#123;alternative&#125;)$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">$\alpha$ = significance level = P(Type I error). Commonly 0.05 or 0.01. One-tailed ($> $ or $< $) vs two-tailed ($\ne $).</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">2 · Test statistic</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$z = \frac&#123;\bar&#123;x&#125; - \mu_0&#125;&#123;\sigma/\sqrt&#123;n&#125;&#125; \;(\sigma \text&#123; known&#125;) \qquad t = \frac&#123;\bar&#123;x&#125; - \mu_0&#125;&#123;s/\sqrt&#123;n&#125;&#125; \;(\sigma \text&#123; unknown&#125;)$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">$t$ has $\text&#123;df&#125; = n-1$. Both standardize the sample mean using the SE. $t \to z$ as $n \to \infty$.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">3 · Decision rule</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$\text&#123;Reject &#125;H_0 \iff \text&#123;p-value&#125; < \alpha \iff |\text&#123;stat&#125;| > z_&#123;\alpha/2&#125;$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">Two-tailed at $\alpha=0.05$: reject if $|z| > 1.96$. Never "accept $H_0$" — only fail to reject.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">4 · Critical z values</div>
    <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(3,1fr);gap:5px;margin-top:8px;">
      <div style="background:var(--gd-bg-3);border:1px solid var(--gd-line-soft);border-radius:7px;padding:7px;text-align:center;">
        <div style="font-size:11px;color:var(--gd-text-2);">90% CI</div>
        <div style="font-family:var(--gd-font-mono);font-size:13px;font-weight:700;color:var(--gd-brand);">1.645</div>
      </div>
      <div style="background:var(--gd-bg-3);border:1px solid var(--gd-line-soft);border-radius:7px;padding:7px;text-align:center;">
        <div style="font-size:11px;color:var(--gd-text-2);">95% CI</div>
        <div style="font-family:var(--gd-font-mono);font-size:13px;font-weight:700;color:var(--gd-brand);">1.960</div>
      </div>
      <div style="background:var(--gd-bg-3);border:1px solid var(--gd-line-soft);border-radius:7px;padding:7px;text-align:center;">
        <div style="font-size:11px;color:var(--gd-text-2);">99% CI</div>
        <div style="font-family:var(--gd-font-mono);font-size:13px;font-weight:700;color:var(--gd-brand);">2.576</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">These are $z_&#123;\alpha/2&#125;$ values. Two-tailed test at 5% → $|z| > 1.96$ to reject.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ THEORY 3: ERROR TYPES & TEST SELECTION ═══ -->
<h2 id="errors">Theory — Error Types &amp; Test Selection</h2>
<p style="font-size:15px;color:var(--gd-text-1);margin-bottom:16px;line-height:1.6;">
  Two kinds of error exist: rejecting a true null (Type I) or missing a real effect (Type II). Power = 1 − β is what good tests maximize.
</p>

<div class="rules-grid">
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Type I and Type II errors</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$\alpha = P(\text&#123;Reject &#125;H_0 \mid H_0\text&#123; true&#125;) \quad \text&#123;(Type I — false alarm)&#125;$$</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$\beta = P(\text&#123;Fail reject &#125;H_0 \mid H_1\text&#123; true&#125;) \quad \text&#123;(Type II — missed effect)&#125;$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">$\text&#123;Power&#125; = 1 - \beta$. Decreasing $\alpha$ increases $\beta$ (harder threshold → more misses).</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Power increases with…</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$\text&#123;Power&#125; \uparrow \; \text&#123;when: &#125; \delta\uparrow,\; n\uparrow,\; \alpha\uparrow$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;"><strong>Effect size $\delta$:</strong> bigger difference from H₀ → easier to detect. <strong>n:</strong> larger sample → tighter SE → easier to detect. <strong>α:</strong> looser threshold → but increases Type I error (tradeoff).</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Which test to use</div>
    <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:1.5fr 1fr;gap:4px 8px;font-size:13px;margin-top:8px;">
      <div style="font-family:var(--gd-font-mono);font-size:11px;color:var(--gd-text-2);border-bottom:1px solid var(--gd-line-soft);padding-bottom:3px;">Situation</div>
      <div style="font-family:var(--gd-font-mono);font-size:11px;color:var(--gd-text-2);border-bottom:1px solid var(--gd-line-soft);padding-bottom:3px;">Test</div>
      <div style="color:var(--gd-text-1);">$\sigma$ known / large $n$</div>
      <div style="color:var(--gd-brand);font-family:var(--gd-font-mono);font-size:12px;">z-test</div>
      <div style="color:var(--gd-text-1);">$\sigma$ unknown, small $n$</div>
      <div style="color:var(--gd-brand);font-family:var(--gd-font-mono);font-size:12px;">t-test (df=n−1)</div>
      <div style="color:var(--gd-text-1);">Variance or categorical</div>
      <div style="color:var(--gd-brand);font-family:var(--gd-font-mono);font-size:12px;">χ²-test</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">p-value — what it actually means</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$p = P(\text&#123;data this extreme&#125; \mid H_0 \text&#123; true&#125;)$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;"><strong>NOT</strong> $P(H_0\text&#123; true&#125;)$. It's the probability of the observation under the null — not the probability that the null is correct. Very commonly confused.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-insights">
  <div class="gd-insight gd-insight--warn">
    <span class="gd-insight__title">Type I vs Type II — the definitions are frequently swapped on the exam</span>
    Type I = <strong>false alarm</strong> (reject a true null — you said effect exists, but it didn't). Type II = <strong>missed effect</strong> (fail to reject a false null — the effect was real but you missed it). A useful mnemonic: α = "alarm" (Type I = alarm that goes off needlessly).
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ VIZ 1: NULL vs ALTERNATIVE ═══ -->
<h2 id="viz1">Interactive 1 — Type I / II Errors &amp; Power</h2>
<p style="font-size:15px;color:var(--gd-text-1);margin-bottom:16px;line-height:1.6;">
  Blue = $H_0$ distribution (null, $\mu=0$). Green = $H_1$ distribution (alternative, $\mu=\delta$). Adjust sliders to see how the tradeoff between $\alpha$, $\beta$, and power changes.
</p>

<div class="gd-formula-panel gd-formula-panel--split">
  <div>
    <div class="gd-formula-label">Definitions</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$\alpha = P(\text&#123;Reject &#125;H_0 \mid H_0\text&#123; true&#125;) \qquad \beta = P(\text&#123;Fail to reject &#125;H_0 \mid H_1\text&#123; true&#125;)$$</div>
  </div>
  <div>
    <div class="gd-formula-label">Power = 1 − β</div>
    <div class="gd-formula-live" id="error-live">—</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-chart">
  <div class="gd-chart__title">Red region = α (Type I) · Orange region = β (Type II) · Green = Power</div>
  <div id="error-chart"></div>
</div>

<div class="error-grid">
  <div class="error-card error-card--alpha">
    <div class="error-card__label">α (Type I)</div>
    <div class="error-card__val" id="alpha-val">—</div>
  </div>
  <div class="error-card error-card--beta">
    <div class="error-card__label">β (Type II)</div>
    <div class="error-card__val" id="beta-val">—</div>
  </div>
  <div class="error-card error-card--power">
    <div class="error-card__label">Power (1−β)</div>
    <div class="error-card__val" id="power-val">—</div>
  </div>
  <div class="error-card error-card--z">
    <div class="error-card__label">Crit value z*</div>
    <div class="error-card__val" id="zstar-val">—</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-controls">
  <div class="gd-controls__title">Parameters (H₀: μ=0, known σ=1)</div>
  <div class="gd-control">
    <label class="gd-control__label"><span class="gd-control__sym">δ</span> Effect size (H₁: μ = δ)</label>
    <span class="gd-control__value" id="delta-val">1.5</span>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-control--full"><input class="gd-control__slider" type="range" id="delta-slider" min="0.2" max="4" step="0.1" value="1.5"></div>
  <div class="gd-control">
    <label class="gd-control__label"><span class="gd-control__sym">α</span> Significance level (one-tailed)</label>
    <span class="gd-control__value" id="alpha-slider-val">0.05</span>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-control--full"><input class="gd-control__slider" type="range" id="alpha-slider-ctrl" min="1" max="4" step="1" value="2"></div>
</div>

<div class="gd-insights">
  <div class="gd-insights__title">Live insights</div>
  <div class="gd-insight gd-insight--active" id="ins-tradeoff">—</div>
  <div class="gd-insight gd-insight--warn" id="ins-practical">—</div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ VIZ 2: P-VALUE ═══ -->
<h2 id="viz2">Interactive 2 — p-value Visualizer</h2>
<p style="font-size:15px;color:var(--gd-text-1);margin-bottom:16px;line-height:1.6;">
  Drag the test statistic or use the slider. The shaded area is the p-value — the probability of seeing a result this extreme (or more extreme) under $H_0$.
</p>

<div class="gd-formula-panel gd-formula-panel--split">
  <div>
    <div class="gd-formula-label">p-value (one-tailed right)</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$p = P(Z \geq z_&#123;\text&#123;obs&#125;&#125; \mid H_0) = 1 - \Phi(z_&#123;\text&#123;obs&#125;&#125;)$$</div>
  </div>
  <div>
    <div class="gd-formula-label">Current</div>
    <div class="gd-formula-live" id="pval-live">—</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-chart">
  <div class="gd-chart__title">Drag the vertical line to move z_obs · Shaded area = p-value</div>
  <div id="pval-chart"></div>
</div>

<div class="pvalue-display" id="pval-display">p = —</div>

<div class="gd-controls">
  <div class="gd-controls__title">Test statistic</div>
  <div class="gd-control">
    <label class="gd-control__label"><span class="gd-control__sym">z</span> Observed z-statistic (drag chart or use slider)</label>
    <span class="gd-control__value" id="zobs-val">1.96</span>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-control--full"><input class="gd-control__slider" type="range" id="zobs-slider" min="-4" max="4" step="0.05" value="1.96"></div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ WORKED EXAMPLES ═══ -->
<h2 id="examples">Worked Examples</h2>

<div class="gd-example">
  <div class="gd-example__q">
    <span class="gd-example__num">Example 1 · Descriptive statistics — mean, median, mode, variance</span>
    <p>Dataset: 3, 5, 5, 7, 10. Find the mean, median, mode, population variance ($\sigma^2$), and sample variance ($s^2$).</p>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-example__body">
    <p><strong>Mean:</strong> $\bar&#123;x&#125; = (3+5+5+7+10)/5 = 30/5 = 6$.</p>
    <p><strong>Median</strong> (sorted: 3,5,5,7,10): middle value $= 5$. &nbsp; <strong>Mode:</strong> $5$ (appears twice).</p>
    <p><strong>Deviations²:</strong> $(3-6)^2=9$, $(5-6)^2=1$, $(5-6)^2=1$, $(7-6)^2=1$, $(10-6)^2=16$. Sum $= 28$.</p>
    <p><strong>Population variance:</strong> $\sigma^2 = 28/5 = 5.6$ &nbsp;($\text&#123;SD&#125; \approx 2.37$).</p>
    <p><strong>Sample variance:</strong> $s^2 = 28/(5-1) = 28/4 = 7$ &nbsp;($s \approx 2.65$).</p>
    <p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--gd-text-2);">The only step that changes: $\div 5$ for population, $\div 4$ for sample. Everything else is identical.</p>
    <div class="gd-example__ans">Mean=6 · Median=5 · Mode=5 · σ²=5.6 · s²=7</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-example">
  <div class="gd-example__q">
    <span class="gd-example__num">Example 2 · GATE 2024 Q34 — Updated / running mean (NAT)</span>
    <p>The sample average of 50 data points is 40. A new data point of value 142 is added. The updated average is ___.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-example__body">
    <p><strong>Recover the sum:</strong> old sum $= 50 \times 40 = 2000$.</p>
    <p><strong>Add new point:</strong> new sum $= 2000 + 142 = 2142$; new count $= 51$.</p>
    <p><strong>New average:</strong> $2142 / 51 = 42$.</p>
    <p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--gd-text-2);">Method: (count × mean) rebuilds the total. Then divide by new count. No need to store all 50 values.</p>
    <div class="gd-example__ans">Updated average = 42</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-example">
  <div class="gd-example__q">
    <span class="gd-example__num">Example 3 · GATE 2024 Q27 — z-score normalization (MCQ)</span>
    <p>Attribute <em>income</em>: min ₹46000, max ₹170000, mean ₹96000, SD ₹21000. The z-score normalized value of ₹106000 is closest to:<br>
    (A) 0.217 &nbsp; (B) 0.476 &nbsp; (C) 0.623 &nbsp; (D) 2.304</p>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-example__body">
    <p><strong>z-score formula:</strong> $z = \dfrac&#123;x - \bar&#123;x&#125;&#125;&#123;s&#125; = \dfrac&#123;106000 - 96000&#125;&#123;21000&#125; = \dfrac&#123;10000&#125;&#123;21000&#125; \approx 0.476$.</p>
    <p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--gd-text-2);">Trap: the min (₹46000) and max (₹170000) are distractors for min-max normalization — irrelevant for z-score. Use only mean and SD. (D) 2.304 = 10000/21000 × wrong formula — dimensional error.</p>
    <div class="gd-example__ans">Answer: (B) 0.476</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-example">
  <div class="gd-example__q">
    <span class="gd-example__num">Example 4 · Two-tailed z-test — hypothesis testing framework</span>
    <p>Test $H_0$: $\mu=100$ vs $H_1$: $\mu\ne100$ at $\alpha=0.05$. Sample of $n=64$ gives $\bar&#123;x&#125;=103$, known $\sigma=16$. Reach a decision.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-example__body">
    <p><strong>SE:</strong> $\sigma/\sqrt&#123;n&#125; = 16/\sqrt&#123;64&#125; = 2$.</p>
    <p><strong>Test statistic:</strong> $z = \dfrac&#123;\bar&#123;x&#125; - \mu_0&#125;&#123;\text&#123;SE&#125;&#125; = \dfrac&#123;103 - 100&#125;&#123;2&#125; = 1.5$.</p>
    <p><strong>Decision:</strong> two-tailed critical value at $\alpha=0.05$ is $\pm1.96$. Since $|1.5| &lt; 1.96$, <strong>fail to reject $H_0$</strong>.</p>
    <p><strong>p-value check:</strong> $p = 2(1-\Phi(1.5)) = 2(1-0.9332) = 0.1336 > 0.05$ — same conclusion.</p>
    <p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--gd-text-2);">Never say "accept $H_0$". The evidence is insufficient to reject — that's different from proof that $H_0$ is true.</p>
    <div class="gd-example__ans">z = 1.5 · |1.5| &lt; 1.96 → Fail to reject H₀</div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ GATE ANGLE ═══ -->
<div class="gd-gate-box">
  <div class="gd-gate-box__title">GATE DA Angle</div>
  <p><strong>Descriptive stats appears every year</strong> — mean/median/z-score/variance. Inference (CI, formal tests) has not been directly tested in 2024–2026, but the fundamentals below could appear in 2027. Invest accordingly.</p>
  <p><strong>$\div n$ vs $\div(n-1)$:</strong> read the problem carefully. "Population variance" or full dataset → $\div n$. "Sample variance" or "$s^2$" → $\div(n-1)$. (2026 Q62 tests this via the identity $\frac&#123;1&#125;&#123;2n^2&#125;\sum_i\sum_j(x_i-x_j)^2 = \frac&#123;1&#125;&#123;n&#125;\sum(x_i-\bar&#123;x&#125;)^2$.)</p>
  <p><strong>z-score uses mean and SD only.</strong> min/max are distractors — those are for min-max normalization, a different formula. Formula: $z = (x - \text&#123;mean&#125;)/\text&#123;SD&#125;$. (2024 Q27)</p>
  <p><strong>Running mean:</strong> new mean $=$ (old count × old mean + new values) / new count. Rebuild the total then divide. (2024 Q34)</p>
  <p><strong>Weighted mean (2025 Q10):</strong> $\bar&#123;x&#125;_w = \sum(f_i x_i)/\sum f_i$ where $f_i$ = frequency/weight. Compute the weighted sum first, then apply any earnings/transform formula.</p>
  <p><strong>Type I vs Type II:</strong> α = P(false alarm) = P(reject true $H_0$). β = P(missed effect). Power = 1 − β. Decreasing α raises β — same data, stricter threshold means more misses.</p>
</div>

